  • Modify the data, it will save your time on data analyzing, modeling.

Part 2a: Handling missing data¶

  • Missing data must be handled before doing any analysis. It could cause serious issue. For example, when you are calculating the mean of a group of large numbers, NaN might be 0 and the mean will be significantly affected.
In [288]:

hdi_na_sum = data.isnull().sum()['HDI for year'] #Get the total number of NaNs in HDI for year column
size = len(data.index) #Get the total row number for the dataframe
missing_percentage = hdi_na_sum/size
print(missing_percentage)

0.699352983465133

69.9% of HDI for year is missing, so I decide to drop this column.

Part 2b: Data Transformation¶

  • Sometimes the catgorical data is represented by string. For example, in this dataset sex is marked as male and female. These cotegorical strings does not mean anything in math so we should convert them to numbers. And notice that the magnitude of these numbers could affect the result so we they have the same magnitude. Therefore, we need an identity matrix to hold all features and each vector in this identity matrix represents one unique feature. This method is called one hot encoding.
In [292]:
data.sex.value_counts() #Display the sex distribution of this dataset
Out[292]:
female    13910
male      13910
Name: sex, dtype: int64
In [293]:
data_sex_dummy = pd.get_dummies(data.sex,prefix = 'sex') # Apply get_dummy(one hot encoding) on the sex column to split the features to two vectors
data = data.join(data_sex_dummy) #Merge the sex identity matrix on original dataframe

  • From the result above, we can see that there are in total 101 countries. If I use one-hot encoding to split these countries, there will be too many categories(vectors) which will cause one hot encoding memory error. Therefore I find another way of processing these data which is group countries by continent.
  • The python extension packagep pycountry_convert could help you convert country to continent. You will need to install the packege before importing.
    pip install pycountry-convert.
    This is the link to pycountry_convert api.
  • Unfortunatelly, pycontrv_convert is no powerful enough to recognize the country name in this dataframe, so we will also need to install country_converter to convert all country names to ISO2 format, and then use the function from pycontry_convert to convert the ISO2 country code to continent.
    pip install country_converter --upgrade
    This is the link to country converter api
In [295]:
import country_converter as coco

cc = coco.CountryConverter()
country_list = data.country.tolist() #Get the country names from dataframe and convert to list.
country_code = cc.convert(names = country_list, to = 'ISO2') # Convert country names to ISO2 country code

data['country_code'] = country_code #Add country code to dataframe
In [296]:

General¶

  • We want to see if there is a general trending for suicide rate over time.

In [327]:
year_df['year'] = year_df.index # Add back year feature to dataframe

x = year_df.year # x is year
y = year_df['suicide_rate'] #y is suicide rate

plt.title('Suiside Rate VS. Year')
ax = sns.scatterplot(x,y)
ax = sns.regplot(x = 'year', y = 'suicide_rate',data = year_df) #plot the linear regression line
  • From the plot we can see that the suiside rate is increasing during 1985 to 1995 and 2015 to 2016, decreasing during 1995 to 2015. At the year 1995, the suiside rate reaches to the history maximun which mean there are nealy 16 out of 100,000 people killed themselves in 1995.
  • The linear regression line indicates that in general the suiside rate is decreasing over time. However, this relationship is not obvious. Therefore, let's add some features to see if we could get some better relationships.

Feature 1: Continent¶

  • Previously we have seen that suicide rate varies among different countries. However, it is too much work to analyze suisde rate in each country. Therefore, instead of nationality, I would like to introduce a more general feature continent to see if this feature would give us some better linear regression lines that indicate the suiside rates over time.
In [325]:
for conti in conti_df.index:
    curr_conti = data[data.continent == conti]
    curr_year = curr_conti.groupby('year').mean()
    curr_year['year'] = curr_year.index
    curr_year['conti'] = conti
    
    x = curr_year.index
    y = curr_year['suicide_rate']
    
    plt.title('Average Suicide Rate VS. Year in Each Continent')
    ax = sns.scatterplot(x,y,data = curr_year,label = conti)
    ax = sns.regplot(x = 'year', y = 'suicide_rate',data = curr_year, label = conti)
  • This plot indicates that in Europe, Oceania,Asia, Africa and North America, there is a decreasing suiside rate over time. In North America however there is an increasing suiside rate over time.
  • The differences of linear regression lines among each continents indicate that the suicide rate varies in different continent. Therefore continent is a feature that will affect suicide rate.

Feature 2: Age¶

Out[315]:
<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x7f6a171afb00>
  • This graph indicates the suiside rate increases as age getting older. In other words, Older people are more likely to kill themselves. Therefore, age is an important factor that affect the suicide rate. Let's see if this feature is giving us some better linear regression lines in suicide rate over time.
In [323]:
for age in age_suiside_df.index:
    curr_age = data[data.age == age]
    curr_year = curr_age.groupby('year').mean()
    curr_year['year'] = curr_year.index
    curr_year['age'] = age
    
    x = curr_year.index
    y = curr_year['suicide_rate']
    
    plt.title('Average Suicide Rate VS. Year')
    ax = sns.scatterplot(x,y,data = curr_year,label = age)
    ax = sns.regplot(x = 'year', y = 'suicide_rate',data = curr_year, label = age)
  • This graph clearly shows that in different age intervals, suiside rate over time is different.
  • For people in age of 5-14, they tends to have a low and constant suicide rate over time. In other words, children keep the good habit of not commit suicides over time.
  • Despite the fact that elders in age of 75+ has the hightest suicide rates among all age intervals, their suicide rate over time is decreasing than any other age intervals. Which means, there is an incresing amount of elders chose not to kill themselves as time goes by.

    curr_year = curr_sex.groupby('year').mean()

    ax = sns.regplot(x = 'year', y = 'suicide_rate',data = curr_year, label = sex)
  • From the graph we can see that two linear regression lines have almost same slope but different y axis intercept, this indicats that overall suiside rate for male is greater than female rate and the suicide rates for both male and female are decreasing over time in a same rate.

    curr_year = curr_generation.groupby('year').mean()
    curr_year['year'] = curr_year.index

    ax = sns.regplot(x = 'year', y = 'suicide_rate',data = curr_year, label = generation)
  • Surprisingly, most generations have a increase suicide rate over time.

Part 3E: Relationship between suicide rate and gdp per capita¶

In [344]:
x = data['gdp_per_capita'] #GDP per capita on x axis
y = data['suicide_rate'] #Suicide rate on y axis
plt.title('Suicide Rate VS. GDP per Capita')
ax = sns.scatterplot(x,y)
ax = sns.regplot(x,y)
  • From the regression line, it is hard to tell the relationship between suicide rate and gdp per capita, but from the scatter, we can clearly tell that suicide rate decreases as gdp per capiita increases. The higher gdp per capita data distribution is more concentrated on low suicide rate.
